29/12/2005
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- The country's anti-corruption commission has concluded there is no efficient system for preventing or combating corruption yet. In an annual report released on Wednesday (28 December), the panel blames continued inefficiency and lack of professionalism in the public administration, failure to observe conflict of interest regulations, and slow judicial proceedings. The commission also criticised a lack of collaboration shown by other institutions. 
In other news, Defence Minister Jovan Manasijevski held a news conference in Skopje Wednesday, voicing general satisfaction with the results of defence sector reforms this year. He cited modernisation of the Macedonian Army's general staff and the ongoing transformation of military structures in line with NATO criteria as the main achievements. (Makfax, Macedonian Government Web site, A1 TV - 28/12/05)
